BOEING 737
SOUTHWEST
SAFETY
INFORMATION
SMOKING IS NOT PERMITTED
ON ANY SCHEDULED FLIGHT.
EXIT SEATING
All seats in the overwing window row have been designated as exit seats.
Federal Aviation Regulations require that all persons seated in a designated exit seat be willing and able to
perform the functions shown on this card in the event of an emergency if a crewmember is not available.
No certificate holder may seat a person in a designated exit seat if the certificate holder determines that it is
likely that the person would be unable to perform one or more of the applicable functions because:
The person lacks sufficient mobility, strength, or dexterity in both arms and hands, and both legs:
1. To reach upward, sideways, and downward to the location of emergency exit and exit-slide operating
mechanisms;
2. To grasp and push, pull, turn, or otherwise manipulate those mechanisms;
3. To push, shove, pull, or otherwise open emergency exits;
To lift out, hold, deposit on nearby seats, or maneuver over the seatbacks to the next row objects the
size and weight of overwing window exit doors;
To remove obstructions similar in size and weight to overwing exit doors;
To reach the emergency exit expeditiously;
To maintain balance while removing obstructions;
To exit expeditiously;
10.
To stabilize an escape slide after deployment; or
To assist others in getting off an escape slide;
The person must be at least 15 years of age or lacks the capacity to perform one or more of the functions
without the assistance of an adult companion, parent, or other relative;
The person must have the ability to read and understand instructions related to emergency evacuation
provided by the certificate holder in printed, handwritten, or graphic form or the ability to understand oral crew
commands in the English language;
The person lacks sufficient visual capacity to perform one or more of the applicable functions without the
assistance of visual aids beyond contact lenses or eyeglasses;
The person lacks sufficient aural capacity to hear and understand instructions shouted by crewmembers,
without assistance beyond a hearing aid;
The person lacks the ability adequately to impart information orally to other passengers; or
The person has:
1. A condition or responsibilities, such as caring for small children, that might prevent the person from
performing one or more of the applicable functions; or
2. A condition that might cause the person harm if he or she performs one or more of the applicable
functions.
In the event of an emergency, follow the directions and hand signals of your crew. If a crewmember is not
available to assist you, follow the instructions on this card and posted signs.
Another seat assignment is required of persons who 1) do not meet the selection criteria; 2) have a condition
that will prevent them from performing the functions; 3) may suffer bodily harm as a result of the functions; or 4)
do not wish to perform the functions.
Notify your Flight Attendant if you have any questions or require reseating.
